============================================================
  PHILOSOPHY
============================================================

Concept:      Social Contract
Branch:       Political
Definition:   Legitimate authority derives from agreement among individuals
Philosopher:  Hobbes/Locke/Rousseau
Example:      People surrender freedoms to government for security and rights

Concept:      Utilitarianism
Branch:       Ethics
Definition:   The right action maximizes total happiness for greatest number
Philosopher:  Bentham/Mill
Example:      Sacrifice one to save five if it maximizes total utility

Concept:      Nihilism
Branch:       Ethics
Definition:   Life has no inherent meaning; values are human inventions
Philosopher:  Nietzsche (diagnosed)
Example:      Without objective grounding, all moral frameworks are invented

============================================================
  QUESTION & ANSWER PAIRS
============================================================

Q1: What is artificial intelligence?
A1: AI is the simulation of human intelligence by machines,
     including learning, reasoning, and problem-solving.
     Types: narrow AI (specific tasks) and general AI
     (human-level across domains).

Q2: What is the Renaissance?
A2: The Renaissance (14th-17th century) was a cultural
     rebirth in Europe featuring renewed interest in Greco-
     Roman art, humanism, and early science. Began in Italy;
     spread across Europe.

Q3: What is photosynthesis?
A3: Photosynthesis converts sunlight, CO2, and water into
     glucose and oxygen: 6CO2 + 6H2O + light → C6H12O6 +
     6O2. It occurs in plant chloroplasts.

Q4: What is machine learning?
A4: Machine learning enables systems to learn from
     experience without being explicitly programmed, using
     data to improve performance automatically.

Q5: What is entropy?
A5: Entropy measures disorder or randomness in a system.
     The Second Law of Thermodynamics states it always
     increases in isolated systems — the arrow of time.

============================================================
  ECONOMICS
============================================================

Concept:    Moral Hazard
Category:   Microeconomics
Definition: Entity takes more risk when not bearing full consequences
Formula:    Conceptual
Economist:  Adam Smith/Pauly
Example:    Banks took excessive risks knowing government would bail them out 2008

Concept:    Opportunity Cost
Category:   Microeconomics
Definition: Value of next-best alternative foregone when choosing
Formula:    OC = forgone alternative value
Economist:  Bastiat
Example:    Studying means forgoing wages you could have earned working

Concept:    Keynesian Economics
Category:   Macroeconomics
Definition: Government fiscal policy stabilizes economy in recessions
Formula:    AD = C + I + G + NX
Economist:  John Maynard Keynes
Example:    2009 US stimulus; 2020-2021 COVID relief spending

